Itis with unfeigned diffidence that I submit to the Public this first attempt at literary labor. I am fully sensible of its many imperfectione, at the same time 1 am conscious of an ability to make it better at some future day, should it meet the favor- able regard of the classical teachers of our land, to whom it is dedIcated as an humble contribution to that cause in which they are now laboring, with such unprecedented zeal. Should it contribute in any measure to a better understanding, or a higher appreciation by our youthful countrymen of a classic author, from whom, beyond almost any other, I have drawn in· struction and delight, I shall not have labored in vain.
